      "post-body":
        '<p>There are two ways to stack: in a pool or by yourself. To stack by yourself you‚Äôll need to meet the dynamic minimum of currently 100,000 STX. If you don‚Äôt meet the minimum, you can still stack by pooling with others. However, even if you do meet the minimum you might want to pool depending on your preferences.<br></p><h2>üåä Pooling</h2><p>A pool will combine all participants‚Äô STX, stack it on their behalf and then distribute the rewards. There are two types of pools: custodial pools such as exchanges and non-custodial pools that use the native stacking smart contract. Unlike custodial pools, non-custodial pools will never be able to access your STX, but you do still need to trust them with the payment of the rewards. The upside to pooling is that you‚Äôll be able to stack even if you don‚Äôt meet the minimum and that a pool will generally stack more than an individual. This decreases the impact that the dynamic minimum has on participants‚Äô rewards.<br></p><h5>Pooling is recommended if:</h5><ul><li>You own less STX than the minimum required for stacking by yourself. You can see the current minimimum on <a href="http://stacking.club">stacking.club</a>.</li><li>You own enough STX to meet the minimum, but an increase in the minimum would have a significant impact on your rewards (more on that in the <em>dynamic minimum</em> section)</li><li>You don‚Äôt mind trusting the pool with the payment of your rewards</li></ul><p>You can discover pools on <a href="https://www.stacks.co/stacking">stacks.co/stacking</a>. If you\'re going to pool, make sure you\'ve researched and trust the pool.<br></p><h2>üßç Stacking by yourself</h2><p>When you stack by yourself you‚Äôll interact with the protocol directly. The upside is that you won‚Äôt have to trust anybody with the payment of your rewards as you‚Äôll receive them directly from miners. The downside is that an increase in the dynamic minimum can have a larger effect on your rewards than it would on a pool.</p><h5>Stacking by yourself is recommended if:</h5><ul><li>You don‚Äôt want to trust a pool with the payment of rewards</li><li>You own at least enough STX to meet the minimum, and ideally enough where an increase in the minimum has a minimal effect on your rewards (more on that below)</li></ul><p>When you stack by yourself, you‚Äôll have to consider how likely it is the minimum will increase, how big an impact an increase would have on your rewards, and the impact of the cooldown cycle.<br></p><h3>üìà The dynamic minimum</h3><p>Every cycle 4,000 reward slots are available for stackers. The minimum required for one reward slots can change from cycle to cycle ‚Äî if an additional 40 million STX starts stacking, the minimum will increase by 10,000 STX. As a result, you could end up with less reward slots if the minimum increases in the future. Imagine the current minimum is 80K and increases to 90K. Here\'s how it would impact your rewards:</p><ul><li>If you stacked 80K, you\'d lose 100% of your reward slots.</li><li>If you stacked 160K, you\'d lose 50% of your reward slots</li><li>If you stacked 400K, you\'d lose 20% of your reward slots</li><li>If you stacked 8M, you\'d lose 12% of your reward slots</li></ul><p>As you see, the impact of an increase in the minimum will have less effect the more you‚Äôre stacking. Pools are also impacted by the dynamic minimum, but they‚Äôll often stack much more than an individual. That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs recommended to stack in a pool if your balance is on the lower end.</p><h2>üìÜ How long to stack</h2><p>Both when pooling and when stacking by yourself, you can decide to stack between 1 to 12 cycles. A cycle is always 2,100 Bitcoin blocks, but the Bitcoin block time varies ‚Äî a cycle generally lasts around 15 days. To decide how many cycles you\'ll stack you\'ll need to keep in mind the cool down cycle, and in case you\'re stacking by yourself the dynamic minimum as well.</p><h3><strong>‚åõ</strong>The cool down cycle</h3><p>After your chosen duration, you‚Äôll have to wait one cycle before you can stack from the same address again, regardless of whether you pooled or stacked by yourself. Your yearly returns (APY) will be higher if you stack for more cycles at a time. For example, If you stack for 3 cycles at a time twice, you‚Äôll be earning rewards 6 out of 8 cycles, with two cool down cycles(‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢-‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢-). If you stacked for 6 cycles at a time, you would have earned rewards 6 out of 7 cycles (‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢-). Revisiting the cool down cycle is part of the considerations for the <a href="https://github.com/stacksgov/sips/discussions/16">Stacks 2.1 upgrade.</a> </p><h3>üìà The dynamic minimum (if you stack by yourself)</h3><p>In general, stacking for more cycles will decrease the impact of the cool down cycle and in turn increase your APY. However, if you‚Äôre stacking by yourself you‚Äôll also have to consider the dynamic minimum. The minimum can change from cycle to cycle, and becomes harder to predict the more cycles you stack. If you‚Äôre stacking an amount where an increase of the minimum will have a significant impact, consider stacking for less cycles or adding a buffer. If you‚Äôre stacking so much that an increase of the minimum will have little impact, consider stacking for longer to maximize the cycles you‚Äôre earning rewards.<br></p><h3>Resources</h3><p><a href="http://hiro.so/wallet">Stacks Wallet</a> by Hiro enables you to pool and stack by yourself with Ledger support.</p><p><a href="https://stacking.club" target="_blank">https://stacking.club</a> will give you insight into stacking data, such as how much STX is stacking for next cycle and how the dynamic minimum has changed in the past.<br></p><p>The <a target="_blank" href="https://paper.dropbox.com/?q=%23stacking">#stacking</a> channel on the <a target="_blank" href="http://stacks.chat">Stacks Discord</a> is where you can ask questions about stacking. Most pools are active on Discord as well and will gladly answer any question you might have.</p><p>Happy stacking!</p>',
